<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1945-08-23T08:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1945-08-23T08:00:00-05:00" n="756" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d756">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">893.014/8–2345: Telegram</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in the Soviet Union</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Harriman</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                            </hi>
                        </head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Moscow</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1945-08-23T16:00:00+03:00">August 23,
                                    1945—4 p.m.</date>
                                <lb/> [Received 4:42 p.m.]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>3024. Although considerable material is now appearing on details of
                            Soviet victories in East Asia and native Manchurian ecstasy over
                            liberation by Red Army (to Department 3024, rptd Chungking 105), Soviet
                            press has thus far neglected to mention that China enjoys sovereignty
                            over Manchuria.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Harriman</hi>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>